04889nam a22006495i 9780231536349DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013020256  a(OCoLC)872624196  a97802315363497 a10.7312/migd166722doi  a(DE-B1597)458437  a(OCoLC)870946779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDS63.2.U5bM5327 2014 4aDS63.2.U5 .M327 2014eb 7aPOL0110102bisacsh04a327.730562231 aMigdal, Joel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShifting Sands :bThe United States in the Middle East /cJoel Migdal.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (424 p.) :b‹B›B&W Photos: ‹/B›8,, ‹B›Maps: ‹/B›3,, ‹B›Graphs: ‹/B›3.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPart I. Introduction -- tPart II. The Cold War and Its Aftermath -- tPart III. A Transformed Region: The Rise and Fall of the Arab Middle East -- tPart IV. The United States and the New Middle East in the Twenty-First Century -- tPart V. Conclusion: Looking Back and Looking Forward -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJoel S. Migdal revisits the approach U.S. officials have adopted toward the Middle East since World War II, which paid scant attention to tectonic shifts in the region. After the war, the United States did not restrict its strategic model to the Middle East. Beginning with Harry S. Truman, American presidents applied a uniform strategy rooted in the country's Cold War experience in Europe to regions across the globe, designed to project America into nearly every corner of the world while limiting costs and overreach.The approach was simple: find a local power that could play Great Britain's role in Europe after the war, sharing the burden of exercising power, and establish a security alliance along the lines of NATO. Yet regional changes following the creation of Israel, the Free Officers Coup in Egypt, the rise of Arab nationalism from 1948 to 1952, and, later, the Iranian Revolution and the Egypt-Israel peace treaty in 1979 complicated this project. Migdal shows how insufficient attention to these key transformations led to a series of missteps and misconceptions in the twentieth century. With the Arab uprisings of 2009 through 2011 prompting another major shift, Migdal sees an opportunity for the United States to deploy a new, more workable strategy, and he concludes with a plan for gaining a stable foothold in the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 70(DE-588)4003846-40(DE-627)10438896X0(DE-576)208852972aAußenpolitik2gnd 70(DE-588)4020517-40(DE-627)1063177680(DE-576)208933697aGeschichte2gnd 70(DE-588)4049043-90(DE-627)1045093250(DE-576)209080264aRegionalpolitik2gnd 70(DE-588)4072885-70(DE-627)1060939320(DE-576)209188553aInternationale Politik2gnd 70(DE-588)4116489-10(DE-627)1043252240(DE-576)209502010aSicherheitspolitik2gnd 70(DE-588)4156741-90(DE-627)1046090010(DE-576)209829168aGeopolitik2gnd 70(DE-588)4209283-80(DE-627)1043532010(DE-576)210191112aEinflussgröße2gnd 70(DE-588)4795237-40(DE-627)3947199720(DE-576)216469082aPolitisches Interesse2gnd 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070982708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/migd1667240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231536349423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docu